    <h3 class="title"><a href="/avatar-isnt-dances-wolves-its-another-plot#comment-11199" class="active">Dances with very smart wolves</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="/user/brad" title="View user profile." rel="nofollow">brad</a> on Sat, 2010-01-23 23:24.</div>
    <div class="content"><p>Indeed, if Cameron truly viewed the Na&#8217;vi as pure primitives, then that is what they are.  It may well be.   However, Cameron doesn&#8217;t say that in the cited interview.   He agrees that the plot is similar to the plot of DWW and other such films, and of course it is.   The question which he has yet to resolve, is is there something deeper under that?</p>

<p>After all, if this is DWW, it&#8217;s DWW where the native&#8217;s spirit gods are real and help defeat the U.S. troops using Costner as an instrument, which is a pretty radical change.  The question being asked in this post is just how is it that Ey-wa is real?   Is it a mystical fantasy reason, or is there an SF reason?   If he does a sequel, we might find out.</p>
